attributes.TITLE: San Diego Trolley - Blue Line
attributes.SHORT_DESC: The San Diego Trolley Blue Line starts at America Plaza in downtown and goes south to San Ysidro at the border crossing for Tijuana.
attributes.DESC1: The San Diego Trolley Blue Line starts at America Plaza in downtown and goes south to San Ysidro at the border crossing for Tijuana.
attributes.DESC2: Buy your ticket at the machine and jump aboard! Pay for a single trip or get a transit day pass good for all trolleys and buses. There are three trolley lines (Green, Blue and Orange) but all the trains are actually bright red!
attributes.DESC3: To go to Mexico, take the Blue Line south from downtown San Diego to San Ysidro station at the border, where the Blue Line ends. Then just walk across the border through the Port of Entry. Don't forget your travel documents, such as passport.
attributes.DESC4: As the Blue Line heads south from downtown, you'll go by the naval dockyard where ships are being built and refurbished.
attributes.HOURS: The trolley generally runs every 15 minutes during the day. Less frequently in the evening.

attributes.TITLE: San Diego Trolley - Orange Line
attributes.SHORT_DESC: The San Diego Trolley Orange Line starts at the Santa Fe Depot train station in downtown and goes east to El Cajon.
attributes.DESC1: The San Diego Trolley Orange Line starts at the Santa Fe Depot train station in downtown and goes east to El Cajon.
attributes.DESC2: Buy your ticket at the machine and jump aboard! Pay for a single trip or get a transit day pass good for all trolleys and buses. There are three trolley lines (Green, Blue and Orange) but all the trains are actually bright red!
attributes.DESC3: The Orange Line terminates in downtown San Diego at the Santa Fe Depot, where you can catch Amtrak (to Los Angeles and points north), and the Coaster commuter train to northern San Diego county.
attributes.DESC4: A ride on Amtrak or the Coaster up the coastline is a nice way to spend the day. A recommended trip is to take the Coaster to Encinitas, a small beach community with a lively downtown and good beaches.
attributes.HOURS: The trolley generally runs every 15 minutes during the day. Less frequently in the evening.

attributes.TITLE: San Diego Trolley - Green Line
attributes.SHORT_DESC: The San Diego Trolley Green Line serves many popular destinations for visitors including the Convention Center, Seaport Village, Gaslamp District, Petco Park, Little Italy, Old Town, Mission Valley and Qualcomm Stadium.
attributes.DESC1: The San Diego Trolley Green Line serves many popular destinations for visitors including the Convention Center, Seaport Village, Gaslamp District, Petco Park, Little Italy, Old Town, Mission Valley and Qualcomm Stadium.
attributes.DESC2: Buy your ticket at the machine and jump aboard! Pay for a single trip or get a transit day pass good for all trolleys and buses. There are three trolley lines (Green, Blue and Orange) but all the trains are actually bright red!
attributes.DESC3: If you use the Green Line to get to an event at the south end of the Convention Center, the Gaslamp Quarter station is closer to that end than the Convention Center station. Take care crossing the railroad tracks as you walk to the Convention Center.

attributes.Title: SANTA FE DEPOT
attributes.Short_Desc: San Diego's downtown train station in a historic building. Served by the Green Line and Orange Line trolley, the Coaster commuter train, and Amtrak's Pacific Surfliner. Take the Green Line to the Convention Center, Old Town, and Mission Valley.

attributes.Desc3: You can take the Amtrak Pacific Surfliner to Orange County, Los Angeles, Santa Barbara, etc. You can take the Coaster commuter train to north San Diego county towns, like Encinitas.
attributes.Desc4: The interior of San Diego's main train station is an elegant public space. The station was built in 1915.
attributes.Desc5: You can get city bus to the airport from here at the bus stop on Broadway, on the northeast corner of the intersection with Kettner Boulevard.

attributes.Title: OLD TOWN TRANSIT CENTER
attributes.Short_Desc: Next to the Old Town State Historic Park, this station is served by the Green Line trolley, Coaster commuter train, & Amtrak. Use the Green Line to get to downtown San Diego, the Convention Center, & Mission Valley. Buses serve Seaworld, beaches, etc
attributes.Desc1: The Green line serves many popular destinations for visitors including the Convention Center, Seaport Village, Gaslamp District, Petco Park, Little Italy, Old Town, Mission Valley and Qualcomm Stadium.
attributes.Desc2: Buy your ticket at the machine and jump aboard! Pay for a single trip or get a transit day pass good for all trolleys and buses. There are three trolley lines (Green, Blue and Orange) but all the trains are actually bright red!

attributes.Desc4: During the day on weekdays bus 30 continues on to Broadway in downtown San Diego. So if you want to visit Pacific Beach, La Jolla, etc from downtown you can get the 30 there instead of coming here on the trolley.
attributes.Desc5: From here you can also take the Amtrak Pacific Surfliner to Orange County, Los Angeles, Santa Barbara, etc. You can take the Coaster commuter train to north San Diego county towns, like Encinitas.
attributes.Hours: The trolley generally runs every 15 minutes during the day. Less frequently in the evening.

attributes.CAPTION:
A whimiscal yet luxurious basement bar and nightclub with a hidden door. The decor is Alice-in-Wonderland meets Prohibition. They focus on wine and spirits here, with a light food menu. This is a great place to go on to after dinner downtown, or go early for happy hour deals. Website

attributes.NAME: Tajima Ramen, East Village
attributes.CAPTION:
Ramen is getting popular in San Diego and this is some of the best in town. Tajima specializes in handmade ramen and delicious small rice bowls. They have craft brews, sake and sodas, friendly, fun staff, and an interior by prolific local designer and fabricator Paul Basile. Website
Neighborhood: East Village
901 E Street, San Diego, CA 92101 at 9th Avenue.

attributes.NAME: The Neighborhood
attributes.DESC1: Walk a few blocks east of the busy Gaslamp Quarter and you're in the East Village, downtown San Diego's gentrifying warehouse district. Restaurants here are less expensive than in the Gaslamp and have a local, less touristy feel. The Neighborhood is a small friendly gastropub with excellent food, and its own secret speakeasy, Noble Experiment, behind a hidden door inside.

attributes.DESC1: Inexpensive, lively place serving excellent breakfast and lunch in historic building. Try the rosemary potatoes or the french toast made with fresh-baked cinnamon bread. Rob Quigley, who designed the new library one block away, just moved in next door.

attributes.NAME: Il Fornaio
attributes.DESC1: On the other side of San Diego Bay from downtown you'll find the Coronado Island Ferry Landing and this branch of the upscale Il Fornaio chain. The great building, food, and views of downtown makes this one of the best deals in town. Eat in the huge dining room or on one of the two patios. It's like having dinner in a Roman villa. A trip here is especially fun using the Coronado public ferry or the San Diego Water Taxi. Or get a cab in downtown for the short ride over the bridge.
